// TEST: exec_match_exprpos_literal_compare
// EXPECT: output "lt;eq;gt"
// EXPECT: targets js, ts, python, rust, go
//
// Expression-position `match` over a literal scrutinee whose arm bodies
// RE-REFERENCE the scrutinee in a comparison, bound into a typed `let`
// (Q-match-exprpos, codegen-completeness P4). This is the TS2367 case.
//
// `let rel: Bool = match n { 0 => n == 0; _ => n < 0 }` lowers (on JS/TS/Go) to
// a `switch`-IIFE. On TS, `switch (n)` narrows `n` to the case's literal type
// (`0`) inside the arm body, so the body's `n == 0` becomes a comparison of the
// literal types `0` and `0`/another literal — `tsc` rejects an apparently
// non-overlapping comparison with TS2367 ("This comparison appears to be
// unintentional…"). The fix hoists the bare-identifier scrutinee into a temp
// (`const __matchN = n; switch (__matchN) …`), so the `switch` narrows the temp
// while the arm body still sees `n` at its declared (un-narrowed) type. The
// IIFE arrow is also annotated with the binding type (`(() : boolean => …)()`).
//
// Go (P4): the IIFE return type prefers the binding's declared type
// (`current_expected_type`) over the function return type, so the `let rel:
// Bool = match …` IIFE is `func() bool { … }()` rather than `func() string`.
//
// The fixture exercises three distinct branches (less-than, equal,
// greater-than) so the arm selection itself is verified, not just compilation.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

fn classify(n: Int) -> String {
  let is_zero: Bool = match n {
    0 => n == 0
    _ => n == 1000
  }
  if (is_zero) {
    return "eq"
  }
  if (n < 0) {
    return "lt"
  }
  return "gt"
}

fn main() -> Void {
  println("${classify(-3)};${classify(0)};${classify(7)}")
}
